    %section
      %h1 What is Life insurance?
      %p
        Insurance is a form of risk management in which the ‘insured’ (usually an individual) transfers the risk of loss to the ‘insurer’ for a certain price known as premium. A life insurance policy is   an arrangement in which the ‘insured’ pays a premium to the ‘insurer’ to reduce the risk of financial burden that his/ her family would have to face in case of sudden death of the insured.
      %p
        For example, take the case of Rohit, a software engineer at a multinational company. He has a wife –Sarita, a homemaker and two children aged 7 and 10. If Rohit dies in an accident, his family will suffer financially. They will not have a source of income to support their living expenses. The future of the children is in jeopardy since they will have no one to support their education. If however, Rohit had a life insurance policy worth Rs 2 crore, the story would have been very different. Sarita would have received Rs 2 crore from the life insurance company upon Rohit’s death. This money and the interest earned on it could have been used to support the family and the childrens’ education.
    %section
      %h1 Why are life insurance policies considered investments?
      %p Typically, how life insurance works is that ‘insured’ (person who avails insurance) is eligible for insurance till a certain age, for which the insured pays a certain amount of money (premium) that is predetermined at initiation of the policy. Life insurance is commonly not sold as a policy in itself. It is packaged along with other investment products and sold to the customer.  When a customer pays a premium, a certain portion is allocated to premium for life insurance and the balance is allocated to the investment corpus. In an investment linked life insurance product, in case the person survives beyond the maturity of the life insurance policy, he is eligible to receive a lump sum of money at maturity.
      %p Life insurance is available in a host of forms. Some of them include:
      %ul
        %li
          %b Term Policy:
          This is a pure life insurance product and unlike other products does not have any investment aspects attached to it. There is an age limit till which the insurer can avail insurance. He has the option of paying regular premiums (quarterly, annually) or pay a onetime lump sum. In case the ‘insured’ survives beyond the maturity of the policy, he simply walks off and does not get any money at maturity.
        %li
          %b Whole Life Policy:
          This policy is active for the whole life of the ‘insured’. The sum assured becomes payable to the legal heir only after the death of the assured.
        %li
          %b Endowment Policy:
          This is an investment related policy in which the ‘insurer’ agrees to pay a certain sum to the insured either in case of death or at maturity, whichever is earlier. The premium in this case is considerably higher than that of the corresponding ‘term policy’ and ‘whole life policy’ and is payable either till death or maturity, whichever is earlier.
        %li
          %b Unit Linked Insurance Policy (ULIP):
          ULIPS are a popular form of investment in which a portion of your premium is used towards servicing your life insurance and the balance is used towards investing. An investor in ULIP has the option to choose how much he wants to allocate between equities and fixed income. He further has the option to revise the allocation as per his discretion.
    %section
      %h1 How much do life insurance policies usually return?
      %p Returns from investment related plans have not been very high. Returns on ULIPs vary based on the performance of equity markets and the allocation of funds between fixed income and equity instruments. On a conservative basis, an investor can expect a return of 5.5%-7% p.a. This is less than what an investor can expect from fixed deposits, bonds and other investments avenues.
    %section
      %h1 What is the tax benefit that life insurance offers?
      %p Premiums paid for life insurance are tax deductible  under section 80 C, whereby the amount paid is reduced from taxable income subject to a maximum limit of Rs 1 lakh.
      %p Payment by an insurer on maturity and death claim are exempt from tax for under section 10(10)(d) of the Income Tax Act. The only policies that are not eligible for exemption on payment or  maturity or claim are Single Premium Policies and policies where the sum assured was less than 5 times the premium paid.
