    %section
      %h1 How should I go about choosing a life insurance policy?
      %p Two tricky questions that you face while purchasing life insurance are: “How much should I insure myself for?” and “Between 2 insurance companies that offer the same products, which one should I go for”?
      %p How much should you insure yourself for?
      %ul
        %li
          The main objective of life insurance is to provide your dependants with sufficient cover such that your sudden death does not hurt them financially. In case you are the only earning member of your family, some of the objectives that you would like your insurance cover to meet are:
          %ul
            %li Clear all debts
            %li Cover your childrens’ education
            %li Meet the medical expenditure of your parents who are dependent on you
            %li Leave your family with sufficient corpus to maintain the same standard of living as long as you can provide for
        %p Typically, you should take a cover which is at least 10 times your current yearly salary.
        %p Between 2 insurance companies that offer the same products, which one should I go for?
        %li While opting which company to invest with, one should always have a look at the claim settlement ratio of the company. The claim settlement ratio of a company is the ratio of the number of claims it settles to the total number of claims it receives.
        %li Any number which is above 85% is considered good to pick an insurance policy from. In case both the companies have a good record, go for the company which has a higher claim settlement ratio. Companies such as Life Insurance Corporation (LIC), HDFC Life ,ICICI Pru Life have good claim settlement ratios.
    %section
      %h1 Editor's take
      %p We recommend that you look at insurance purely from the point of view of risk  management and not as an investment option. It is advisable that you buy a ‘term policy’ for the intended sum and invest the remaining money in assets such as fixed deposits which pay you higher returns on an assured basis. Consider the following scenario:
      %p Raj is a 26 year techie drawing a handsome salary. He wants to buy a life insurance policy that provides him with coverage of Rs 1 crore till the age of 60 years. He is considering investing in an investment cum insurance plan where the premium is approx. Rs 50,000 p.a. for 34 years (till he turns 60 years). In case he alive till maturity, he is entitled to receive approx. 90 lakhs. Sounds exciting right?
      %p Here is an alternative: For a premium of about  Rs 15,000 p.a. he can easily purchase a life insurance policy that meets his criteria. He can use the remaining amount to invest in long term fixed deposits which currently pay almost 9.5% p.a. (he will have to invest in ” a new FD each year).  At this rate he stands to earn a whopping Rs 1.01 crore at the age of 61 which out beats the investment cum insurance policy. Sounds good? The party is not over yet. In the first case, Raj is tied up with a long term commitment of Rs 50,000 p.a for 34 years. In any year in case he fails to pay his premium, he stands the risk of his policy being suspended and eventually lapsing whereas in the second case his premium commitment is much lower. In case in a given year he cannot cough out the amount as per the original plan, he can avoid being penalised by paying only Rs 15,000 instead of Rs 50,000 that he would have to pay in the first case.
      %p In our view, 34 years is a very long term view and ideally Raj should  invest in a diversified portfolio consisting of equal shares of equity, gold and fixed deposits. A diversified portfolio like this one is relatively less risky (more risky than only fixed deposits) but the gains that an investor stands to earn are very high.
      %p
        %b Note:
        In the above case, we have made some very simple assumptions to make it easy for our readers to understand the case. Fixed deposit rates are subject to change with time and investors face the risk of interest rates decreasing.

